  "prompt": "How is the ionization energy of hydrogen atom determined?",
  "response": "The ionization energy of a hydrogen atom can be determined using the principles of quantum mechanics and the Bohr model of the atom. Here's a step-by-step explanation:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Bohr Model of the Hydrogen Atom**\nThe hydrogen atom consists of a single proton in the nucleus and a single electron orbiting the nucleus. The Bohr model describes the electron in specific quantized energy levels.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Energy Levels in the Hydrogen Atom**\nThe energy of the electron in the \\( n \\)-th energy level is given by:\n\\[\nE_n = -\\frac{13.6 \\, \\text{eV}}{n^2}\n\\]\nwhere \\( n \\) is the principal quantum number (\\( n = 1, 2, 3, \\dots \\)).\n\n---\n\n### **3. Ionization Energy**\nThe ionization energy is the minimum energy required to remove the electron from the ground state (\\( n = 1 \\)) to infinity (\\( n = \\infty \\)). At infinity, the electron is no longer bound to the nucleus, and its energy is zero.\n\n\\[\n\\text{Ionization energy} = E_{\\infty} - E_1\n\\]\n\n---\n\n### **4. Calculation**\n- The energy of the ground state (\\( n = 1 \\)) is:\n\\[\nE_1 = -\\frac{13.6 \\, \\text{eV}}{1^2} = -13.6 \\, \\text{eV}\n\\]\n- The energy at infinity (\\( n = \\infty \\)) is:\n\\[\nE_{\\infty} = 0 \\, \\text{eV}\n\\]\n- The ionization energy is:\n\\[\n\\text{Ionization energy} = 0 \\, \\text{eV} - (-13.6 \\, \\text{eV}) = 13.6 \\, \\text{eV}\n\\]\n\n---\n\n### **Result**\nThe ionization energy of the hydrogen atom is **13.6 electronvolts (eV)**. This value has been experimentally confirmed and is consistent with spectroscopic measurements.",
